  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription on the Pine-Moon Hall
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Jinggjie wrote in his poem:
    'The autumn moon casts its radiant light,
    The winter ridge shows its solitary pine.'

    Pine and moon—at no season do they lack beauty. Yet why did he compose specifically of autumn and winter? There must be something he sought to capture. When silver streams of starlight fall and heaven's realm turns crystalline, the light gleams pure and white. Snow rages and wind shrieks, the year wanes and cold deepens, and the pine stands verdant and solemn, bearing the noble character of late decay. Its bearing is pristine, untouched by a speck of dust. This is what is meant by radiance and grace—and this is what Jinggjie cherished, the very meaning Zineng gave the hall.

    Pine and moon in autumn and winter are but two separate things. But here, beside the pine grove, when the moon comes to illuminate, heaven and earth converge within a few steps, and all four seasons gather in a single moment. True, Jinggjie also sang of spring waters and summer clouds, yet Zineng chose among them with purpose. Was there not wisdom in this selection?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jinggjie (靖節) refers to Tao Qian (陶潛), the renowned Eastern Jin poet. This is an allusion to his famous poem 'Substance, Shadow, and Spirit.'
  - key: ''
    value: Zineng (子能) is the person for whom the Pine-Moon Hall (松月堂) was named, and the subject of the inscription.
